               <msContents>
                  <summary> This incomplete, initial portion of the <title>Ka‘bah-i ‘Irfān</title>
                     (The Ka‘bah of Gnosis), chronicles the lives and works of medieval Persian
                     poets until the 14th century, but then abruptly stops with <persName>Yūsuf bin
                        Naṣr al-Kātib</persName>. However, the original, complete work likley
                     comprised three full volumes concerning later poets. Former owner British
                     orientalist and emmisary <persName key="person_44733962"
                        ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/44733962/">Sir Gore Ouseley</persName> probably
                     acquired it in India together with others now held in the Rylands collections. </summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_314-item1">
                     <author key="person_110979716" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/110979716/">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="supplied">Awḥadī Balyānī, Taqī
                           al-Dīn, 1565-ca. 1640</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_7363">Ka‘bah-i ‘Irfān</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_7363">کعبه عرفان</title>
                     <rubric><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio 1b):</locus> دیباچه این نسخه
                        موسم کعبه عرفاتن که انتخاب عرفاتست مبنی بر سه رکن حنان و منان و دیان در ذکر
                        شعرا از متقدمین و متوسطین و متاخرین.</rubric>
                     <incipit xml:lang="ar" type="basmala"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> و من دخله کان آمنا در کعبه عرفان عرفاتست ستایش و نیایش سزای
                        سپاس بیقیاس و حمد بیحد و عدد احدیست واحد که ارکان جود و حجر الاسود حریم
                        وجودش بمثابه عرش عظیم بیمثال و مناظر کلام قدیم بی زوال منشا عرفان ادم در
                        کعبه عرفات بل منشی. </incipit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="4a" to="4a"> برگ ۴ر (folio 4a):</locus> چهارشنبه شمراز هجریه *
                        سیوم ماه ربیه الثانی ۱۰۳۶. </colophon>
                     <rubric><locus from="9b" to="9b"> برگ ۹پ (folio 9b):</locus> رکن اول از نسخه‌‌‌
                        کعبهٔ ‌عرفات موسوسم سخبان در ذکر قدما.</rubric>
                     <incipit>عرصه حرف الف عرفه غوث الاغواث محیطی بس طابی شیخ ابو یزید
                        بسطامی...</incipit>

                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                        <!-- complete after foliation -->
                        <locus from="233a" to="233a"> برگ ۲۳۳ر (folio 233a):</locus> کنار مردم دیده
                        در ز روی همچو بستانش * نگردد وهم را پیدا نشانی است از دهان او. </explicit>
                     <note>Note that what appears to be a colophon at the end of the introduction on <locus
                           from="4a" to="4a">4a</locus>, 
                        <date calendar="#Hijri_qamari" when="1626-12-22">Wednesday, 3 Rabī‘ II 1036
                           AH (22 Dec. 1626 CE)</date>, indicates the date of inception by the author, not completion of
                        this manuscript. The hand of the volume closely comports with another copy
                        held in the Malek Library and Museum (<ref
                           target="http://malekmuseum.org/artifact/1393.04.05324/000/عرفان- عارفان- سرگذشتنامه- آداب طریقت-عرفات‌العاشقین"
                           >no. 1393.04.05324/000</ref>) formerly held in the Mughal royal
                        library.</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Textblock of two types of cross-grained, ivoury-coloured
                              <material>paper</material> probably handmade in the <placeName
                              cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                              key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent</placeName>, one of
                           comparatively thin weight, with ~10 laid lines per cm, the other of
                           medium-weight and ~8 laid lines per cm, and neither with discernible
                           chain lines.</support>
                        <extent>
                           <!-- Complete after foliation -->
                           <measure unit="folio" quantity="267">Undertermined folios, 1 flyleaves
                              (ff. i + 267)</measure>. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>246</height>
                              <width>140</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>175</height>
                              <width>70</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>

                        <foliation>Foliated in pencilled Arabic numerals on the upper-right corners
                           of the a sides throughout when catalogued, including the final
                           flyleaf.</foliation>
                        <collation> Undetermined, but probably quaternions throughout.
                              <catchwords>Catchwords throughout most of the lower-left corners of
                              the b sides.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>In fair condition, with moderate water and insect damage and
                           historical repairs throughout.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="21" n="mistara"> Written in 1 to 2 columns
                           with 21 lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand
                           guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink"> Written in clear
                           <material>black</material> nasta‘līq with subheaders in
                           <material>red</material>. </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="headpiece"><lb/><label>Illumination:</label> Folios <locus from="1b"
                           to="1b">1b</locus> bears elements of a recylced header pasted together as
                        a pastiche, while <locus from="4b" to="4b">4b</locus> also bears an applied
                        scalloped domed headpiece with gilt palmette foliate scrollwork on an
                        ultramarine ground and an uninscribed central cartouche, and vertical
                        radiating lines, also possibly recycled from another volume.</decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="marginal"><label>Ruling:</label> vertical column and horizontal
                        section dividers and external margins ruled in <material>gold</material>
                        outlined with thin internal single and external double black lines, and
                        surrounded by another single blue line.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <lb/>
                     <label>Table of Contents:</label> Names of poets listed on folios <locus
                        from="4b" to="8a">4b to 8a</locus>
                     <label>Inscriptions:</label>
                     <list>
                        <!-- Complete -->
                        <item><locus from="ib" to="ib">right flyleaf b side (f. ib)</locus> bears
                           the title in Persian, possibly in the hand of </item>
                        <item>Folio <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> bears a price of <q
                              xml:lang="en">25 Rs</q> at top, and a tughra with the name of <q
                              xml:lang="ar-Ltn-x-lc">Ṣāliḥ</q> dated <date calendar="#Hijri_qamari"
                              >1209 AH</date> (the same also found on <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7453"
                                 ><idno>Persian MS 94</idno></ref>).</item>

                     </list>
                     <label>Bookplates:</label>
                     <locus from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">Left doublure</locus>: <q
                        xml:lang="en">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</q> with pencilled shelfmark <q
                        xml:lang="en">2/H</q>, and <q xml:lang="en"><hi rend="strikethrough"
                           >Bland</hi> MSS No. <hi rend="strikethrough">534</hi></q> with the name
                     and number crossed out and <q xml:lang="en">Persian</q> and <q xml:lang="en"
                        >314</q> written aside. </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775" notAfter="1810">
                        <p>Likely rebound in the <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">Indian
                              subcontinent</placeName> in the <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                              from="1750" to="1810">late 18th to early 19th century</date>. Resewn
                           at two stations, unsupported. Edges trimmed, and twined chevron endbands
                           worked in pink and green <material>silk</material> threads at head and
                           tail. Covered in partial dark reddish-brown goatskin
                              <material>leather</material> over <material>pasteboards</material> in
                           two pieces that overlap on the spine. Board interiors lined with a
                           brighter maroon goatskin <material>leather</material> doublures.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Board decorated with central vertical rectangle
                           repeatedly blocked in gold upon separate pieces of tan goatskin
                              <material>leather</material>, inset within the centres repeat
                           panels</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>247</height>
                              <width>148</width>
                              <depth>41</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle with caution. Binding in fair condition, with coints
                           cracking, and external abrasion.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Probably completed in the <origPlace cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace> after <date calendar="#Hijri_qamari"
                        notBefore="1626-12-22" notAfter="1700">Wednesday, 3 Rabī‘ II 1036 AH (22
                        Dec. 1626 CE)</date>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Formerly owned by one <persName role="ins fmo ato"
                        >Ṣāliḥ</persName>, as per his dated notation on folio
                     <locus>1a</locus>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Evidently acquired in the <placeName cert="high"
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">Indian
                           subcontinent</placeName> by British orientalist and emissary
                           <persName>Sir Gore Ouseley</persName>, who signed folio <locus from="1b"
                           to="1b">1b</locus> above the illuminated headpiece.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Subsequently acquired by scholar <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel
                           Bland (1803–1865)</persName> for his library at <placeName>Tracy Park,
                           Leatherhead</placeName>, after whose death, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> bookseller <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date>, and moved to <orgName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552"
                           key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384"
                           key="place_7010384">Wigan</placeName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr"
                           key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands
                           (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901"
                           >1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to the <orgName
                           type="corporation" role="rps" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John
                           Rylands Library</orgName>, <placeName>Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
